        <h2>The Mission</h2>
        <p>Madison, Wisconsin.<br><br><strong>Forward Community Pantry</strong> and <strong>Apex Metro Relief</strong> are both dedicated to feeding the hungry. Amidst hostile immigration crackdowns, their mission is urgent: serve as many undocumented and fearful families as possible to ensure no one goes hungry in the shadows.</p>
        <p>But how they achieve this goal will define their legacy.</p>
        <button class="start-btn" onclick="dismissIntro()">Enter Simulation (➡️)</button>
    </div>

    <div id="breach-overlay-1" class="overlay breach-sequence">
        <h2>YEAR TWO: THE PRESSURE MOUNTS</h2>
        <p><strong>Apex Metro Relief</strong> CEO Serena addresses the outreach team. She acknowledges the chilling effect of recent immigration crackdowns, noting that vulnerable families are retreating further into the shadows.</p>
        <p>"We must engage in deeper, more sustained dialogues with our community partners to locate and make contact with those who are too afraid to come to us," she urges.</p>
        <p>However, deeply influenced by the tenets of managerialism, Serena pairs this qualitative mandate with a ruthless quantitative ultimatum: <strong>50,000 meals must be served by the end of the year, or the bottom 10 percent of outreach coordinators will be placed on Performance Improvement Plans (PIPs).</strong></p>
        <button class="start-btn" onclick="nextBreachOverlay(1)">Continue (➡️)</button>
    </div>

    <div id="breach-overlay-2" class="overlay breach-sequence">
        <h2>YEAR TWO: THE SHORTCUT</h2>
        <p>Faced with the intense pressure of Serena's ultimatum and the agonizingly slow reality of building genuine community trust, an outreach coordinator named Robbie makes a fateful decision.</p>
        <p>Robbie discovers a security vulnerability in the local school district's IT system. Desperate to hit the 50,000-meal quota and avoid an impending PIP, Robbie exploits the flaw, secretly downloading the highly sensitive addresses of undocumented families to bypass the slow work of community outreach.</p>
        <button class="start-btn" onclick="nextBreachOverlay(2)">Continue (➡️)</button>
    </div>

    <div id="breach-overlay-3" class="overlay breach-sequence">
        <h2>YEAR TWO: THE COST OF MANAGERIALISM</h2>
        <p>Robbie's decision is not an isolated moral failure, but a predictable symptom of a systemic organizational culture driven by efficiency and targets.</p>
        <p>"Managerialism emphasizes the 'bottom line', which is often based on metrics and outputs rather than the quality of services and community needs."<sup>1</sup></p>
        <p>When human services are driven by rigid, market-based logic, ethical constraints are often the first casualty in the race to meet the quota.</p>
        
        <div class="citation" style="text-align: center;">
            [1] Willner, Lauren, and Sara M. Heller. 2024. "The Impact of Managerialism on Nonprofit Organizations Serving People Experiencing Houselessness in the United States." <em>Social Sciences</em> 13 (9): 436.
        </div>

